'''Generación del 51''' is a designation for one of a series of "generations" of Spanish composers, identifying a group born between 1924 and 1938.
Members of this group of composers from the Basque and Castilian-speaking regions of Spain include {{harv|Perez Castillo|2001}}: *[[Carmelo Bernaola|Carmelo Alonso Bernaola]] (1929–2002) *{{Interlanguage link multi|Miguel Alonso (composer)|es|3=Miguel Alonso Gómez|lt=Miguel Alonso}} (1925–2002) *[[Angel Arteaga]] *[[Cristóbal Halffter]] (b. 1930) *{{Interlanguage link multi|Ramón Barce|es}} (1928–2008) *[[Agustín Bertomeu]] (b. 1929) *{{Interlanguage link multi|Amando Blanquer|es|3=Amando Blanquer Ponsoda}} (1935–2005) *{{Interlanguage link multi|Francisco Calés|es|3=Francisco Calés Otero}} (1925–1985) *{{Interlanguage link multi|Manuel Castillo|es}} (1930–2005) *[[Juan José Falcón Sanabria]] (b. 1936) *[[Antón García Abril]] (b. 1933) *{{Interlanguage link multi|Agustín González Acilu|es}} (b. 1929) *[[Juan Hidalgo Codorniu|Juan Hidalgo]] (b. 1927) *{{Interlanguage link multi|Ángel Oliver|es|3=Ángel Oliver Pina}} (1937–2005) *[[Luis de Pablo]] (b. 1930) *[[Claudio Prieto]] (b. 1934) In their earlier works, members of this generation tended toward the avant-garde, with post-Webernian [[serialism]] evident in the work of Halffter and Luis de Pablo in particular. By the end of the 1970s a mellowing of their language becomes apparent, and during the 1980s many of them began to turn to [[tonality]] of one sort or another {{harv|Perez Castillo|2001}}.
The Catalan members of this generation are associated with the reforming and renewing tendencies that emerged after the post-Civil War isolation ({{harvnb|Gómez|2001}}; {{harvnb|Perez Castillo|2001}}): * {{Interlanguage link multi|Xavier Benguerel i Godó|ca}} (b. 1931) * {{Interlanguage link multi|Joan Guinjoan Gispert|ca}} (b. 1931) * [[Josep Mestres Quadreny]] (b. 1929) * [[Josep Soler i Sardà]] (b. 1935) Soler's compositional palette involves serial techniques, and he is particularly noted for his dramatic music {{harv|Perez Castillo|2001}}.
==References== * {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Gómez|2001}}|reference=Gómez, Maricarmen. 2001. "Barcelona". ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by [[Stanley Sadie]] and [[John Tyrrell (musicologist)|John Tyrrell]]. London: Macmillan Publishers.}} * {{wikicite|ref={{harvid|Perez Castillo|2001}}|reference=Perez Castillo, Belen. 2001. "Spain, §I: Art music: 6. 20th century". ''The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians'', second edition, edited by Stanley Sadie and John Tyrrell. London: Macmillan Publishers.}}
